<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Dr Nigel Perry (CYS0122)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence f</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rom Dr Nigel Perry (CYS0122)</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:15.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">yclist safety is important, just as is pedestrian and motorist safety.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:15.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Cycling should be promoted for what it is: a healthy activity whose benefits far outweigh its costs and which is beneficial to the </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">participant and Society as a whole.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:15.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Active transport modes should be encouraged. Appropriate infrastructure should be provided where needed. This may include restrictions on non-active transport modes that have an overall negative effect on the environment</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt"> in a particular area.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:15.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Bicycle helmet legislation and promotion have no place in a bicycle safety program.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:15.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Recommendations in the Highway Code to wear a helmet should be removed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">The Committee did not explicitly ask for views on the role of helmets in cycl</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">ing safety. However, while British I have been resident in New Zealand for some years and have first hand experience of how wrong and counterproductive promoting or legislating bicycle helmets is. It is important than the UK does not make the same mistakes</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Bicycling is Beneficial</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:15.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Experts agree that bicycling is beneficial, the benefits accrued to the individual and Society exceed the costs incurred.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:15.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Where the experts sometimes differ is not over the existence of the benefit but over its magnitude – finding</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">s range from modest to significant, often dependent on the context considered, such as individual locality or a whole country. For a recent whole country result we can turn to the Government’s Active Transport Strategy, 2010</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Does the safety risk of cycli</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ng outweigh the health benefits?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">The answer is, quite clearly, no: the actual risk of cycling is tiny. There is one cyclist death per 33 million kilometres of cycling, while being sedentary presents a much greater risk. Over 50,000 people die in the UK eac</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">h year due to coronary heart disease related to insufficient physical activity, compared to around 100 cyclists killed on the road. Research suggests that safety risks are outweighed by the health benefits by a factor of around twenty to one.</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:15.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">The truth beh</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">ind the cyclists’ saying “If you’re cycling you’re winning” is clear, but it is an abbreviation of the true situation:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">The individual choosing to cycle wins; they gain a health benefit, they reduce their transport costs, etc. Cyclists on average live longe</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">r.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">8.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Society also benefits; there is less demand on health services, reduced congestion on the roads, lower environmental pollution (which incidentally is a significant killer), etc.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">8.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Business also benefits; healthier people are happier, and healthier happier</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt"> people are more productive –</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">some countries have run schemes where employers donate bicycles to their employees if they use them a few times a week to ride to work, and businesses have participated because it makes financial sense to do so.</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 13.25pt; padding-left:15.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">The myth that </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">cycling is a cost rather than a benefit is something that was nurtured by those promoting bicycle helmets – it is clearly an effective, if immoral, way to create a market.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">That’s not to say cycling is perfectly safe either; just like any activity, from sho</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">wering to driving, people get injured; just that overall the benefits outweigh the costs – just as with showering!</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Why Bicycle Helmet Legislation And Promotion Is Bad</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Cycling, in ordinary everyday clothing, for the individual, Society and business is win, </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">win, win.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Bicycle helmet legislation fines bicyclists for providing the above benefits; for improving their health while saving Society money.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">It is clearly absurd to fine people for saving Society money, and there are also rights and discrimination issues</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt"> – bicycle helmet legislation is at best simply incompatible with British standards</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Bicycle helmet promotion is also counter-productive:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">14.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">It creates the false impression that the costs of bicycling outweigh the benefits, while the reverse is true, however</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt"> much effort is put into avoiding this problem</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">14.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Helmet promotion has therefore, wherever undertaken, over sold the minimal protection that helmets provide</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt"> in order to counter the false impression of the dangers of bicycling.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">14.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Overselling any safety device</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt"> is counterproductive, due to risk compensation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">14.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">The result is that the, already minimal, benefit is negated.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">14.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Bicycle helmets are commercial products; marketing is up to the manufacturers not the Government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">14.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">However as safety devices there marketing must b</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">e controlled, that is where the Government has a role –</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">in avoiding specious claims etc.</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">There is also an unavoidable aspect of victim blaming:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">15.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">You start with an activity where the benefits outweigh the costs and yet argue that participants are somehow irr</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">esponsible if they don’t wear helmets</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">15.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Today in Australia and New Zealand it is a common view among the public that un-helmeted bicyclists should not be covered by national health care.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">15.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Yet those bicyclists are </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">reducing</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt"> Society’s costs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">15.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">And are invariably</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">victims</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt"> when serious injuries or deaths occur.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusions</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Cyclist safety is important, just as is pedestrian and motorist safety.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Cycling should be promoted for what it is: a healthy activity whose benefits far outweigh its costs and which is benefic</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">ial to the participant and Society as a whole.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Active transport modes should be encouraged. Appropriate infrastructure should be provided where needed. This may include restrictions on non-active transport modes that have an overall negative effect on the </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">environment in a particular area.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Bicycle helmet legislation is simply wrong and cannot be considered within the UK system.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Bicycle helmet promotion is best avoided; its costs far outweigh its benefits.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Recommendations in the Highway Code to wear a helmet </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">should therefore be removed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18.75pt; padding-left:9.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">Bicycle helmet manufacturers should be required to clearly specify the level of protection provided, and to be able to prove those claims.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Active Travel Strategy</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt">, Department for Transport/Department of Health, UK, 22 Feb 2010</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt"> These standards are by no means new, we find them in liberalism in the 17C:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 16.65pt 5pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt">… the only purpose for which power can be rightfully exercised over any member of a civilized community, against his will, is to prevent harm to others. His own good, either phy</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt">sical or moral, is not a sufficient warrant. He cannot rightfully be compelled to do or forbear because it will be better for him to do so … because, in the opinions of others, to do so would be wise, or even right. These are good reasons for remonstrating</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt"> with him, or reasoning with him, or persuading him or entreating him, but not for compelling him, or visiting him with any evil, in case he do otherwise.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 16.65pt 5pt 14.2pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt">from On Liberty, John Stuart Mill, 1859</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt">Echoes of these ideas are found in our present day views on </span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt">human rights, discrimination and justice.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn3"></a><a href="#_ednref3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt"> The New Zealand Government, when working on an active transport strategy, once stated that they had “shot ourselves in the foot” with the promotion of bicycle helmets.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn4"></a><a href="#_ednref4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt"> Bicycle helmets are designed, due to unavo</span><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt">idable limitations, for cycle-only incidents below about 10mph.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn5"></a><a href="#_ednref5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt"> For example the New Zealand Government chose the slogan “Bare head, Knucklehead”… with obvious connotations. But what could they have chosen without negative connotations?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p></body></html>